3.5 Inspecting environments
R lets you look at all of this directly. The rlang package provides the most readable tools.
library(rlang)

f &lt;- function() {
  a &lt;- 1
  b &lt;- 2
  env_print()       # prints this environment and its parent
}
f()
# &lt;environment: 0x...&gt;
# parent: &lt;environment: global&gt;
# bindings:
#   * a: &lt;dbl&gt;
#   * b: &lt;dbl&gt;
You can also build environments by hand and use them as plain data structures. This is the trick behind R6 classes, behind the cache in memoise, behind Shiny’s tracking of reactive dependencies, and behind targets’ record of pipeline state. We will meet all four.
e &lt;- new.env(parent = emptyenv())
e$counter &lt;- 0
e$counter &lt;- e$counter + 1
ls(e)                # "counter"
identical(e, e)      # TRUE

4.3 Hidden state and the superassignment arrow
Closures give R something that looks like private, mutable state. The mechanism is the superassignment operator, written &lt;&lt;-. The ordinary arrow &lt;- creates or updates a binding in the current environment. The double arrow walks up the parent chain looking for an existing binding of that name, and modifies the first one it finds.
make_counter &lt;- function(start = 0) {
  count &lt;- start
  list(
    increment = function() {
      count &lt;&lt;- count + 1     # modify count in the parent environment
      invisible(count)
    },
    reset = function() {
      count &lt;&lt;- start
      invisible(count)
    },
    value = function() count
  )
}

c1 &lt;- make_counter()
c1$increment(); c1$increment(); c1$increment()
c1$value()       # 3

c2 &lt;- make_counter(100)
c2$value()       # 100, completely independent of c1
Each call to make_counter() creates a fresh environment containing count. The three inner functions all close over that same environment, so they share one counter. From outside, c1 and c2 look like little objects with methods, and they keep separate state, but there is no class system here at all, only environments and functions. This is sometimes called functional object-oriented programming, and it is the conceptual seed from which R6 grows later in the book.
Notice that this only works because of the reference behaviour of environments from the previous chapter. The three inner functions are not each given a private copy of count. They share one environment by pointer, so when increment changes it, value sees the change.

4.5 Memoise, in eight lines
To make all of this concrete, here is the entire idea of memoise::memoise(), built from scratch using only a closure and an environment.
memoise &lt;- function(f) {
  cache &lt;- new.env(parent = emptyenv())
  function(...) {
    key &lt;- rlang::hash(list(...))
    if (is.null(cache[[key]])) {
      cache[[key]] &lt;- f(...)
    }
    cache[[key]]
  }
}

slow &lt;- function(x) { Sys.sleep(1); x^2 }
fast &lt;- memoise(slow)

system.time(fast(4))    # about 1 second
system.time(fast(4))    # essentially zero, served from cache
Look at the structure against everything so far. We make an empty environment to use as a cache, living on the heap. We return a wrapper function that, on each call, hashes its arguments, looks the hash up in the cache, and either returns the stored value or computes a fresh one and stores it. The wrapper closes over both f and cache. Each call to memoise mints a new, private cache. The real memoise package adds robustness (disk backends, expiry, better hashing) but the engine is exactly this. Caching, at bottom, is just a closure holding a table.






NoteThis is the seed of two later chapters



Hold this eight-line memoise in mind. In Chapter 7 we will see that a Shiny reactive() is essentially this same pattern, a closure wrapping a computation and caching its result, with the extra twist that the cache is invalidated automatically when inputs change. In Chapter 8 we will see that targets is again this pattern, with the cache living on disk and surviving across sessions. One idea, three scales.

5.4 Quosures: a friendlier interface
The rlang package wraps promises in a tidier, first-class object called a quosure: an expression bundled with the environment it came from. Promises are an internal mechanism that R uses as it runs. Quosures are objects you can store in a variable, pass to other functions, modify, and evaluate on demand.
library(rlang)

capture &lt;- function(x) {
  q &lt;- enquo(x)                              # capture as a quosure
  cat("Expression: ", deparse(get_expr(q)), "\n")
  cat("Environment:", environmentName(get_env(q)), "\n")
  eval_tidy(q)
}

a &lt;- 5
capture(a + 7)
If you have ever written a helper like the following and wondered what the curly braces do, here is the answer.
my_summary &lt;- function(data, group_col) {
  data |&gt;
    dplyr::group_by({{ group_col }}) |&gt;
    dplyr::summarise(n = dplyr::n())
}
{ group_col } is shorthand for “capture the unevaluated expression the caller passed for group_col, and splice it into the group_by call”. Without lazy evaluation and quosures this could not work: by the time group_by received the argument, R would have already tried to evaluate group_col as an ordinary variable, found nothing, and stopped with an error. The whole tidyverse style of naming columns without quotes rests on the promise mechanism in this chapter.

show_parents &lt;- function() {
  list(
    definition = environmentName(environment(show_parents)),
    calling    = environmentName(parent.frame())
  )
}

g &lt;- function() show_parents()
g()







NoteAnalogy: who wrote me versus who sent me



The definition environment is your birthplace: where you were written, fixed forever. The calling environment is the return address on the envelope of whoever just sent you a task: different every time you are called. Lexical scoping says you look up words in the dictionary of your birthplace, not the dictionary of whoever sent the envelope.

6.3 Conditions: errors, warnings, and messages
R has an unusually well-designed system for signalling and handling exceptional situations, and it is poorly known. It is built on the same stack-walking machinery, and it rewards learning, especially for anyone building pipelines that must not fall over at the first problem.
Two functions carry most of the weight, and the difference between them is the whole point.
tryCatch() catches a condition and unwinds the stack: execution leaps out of all the intermediate frames and resumes after the tryCatch call. Use it when you want to abandon the failed work and recover.
withCallingHandlers() runs your handler without unwinding the stack. The original computation is still sitting there, paused, and can be resumed. Use it when you want a side effect, such as logging, without abandoning the work in progress.
safe_fit &lt;- function(model_fn, data) {
  withCallingHandlers(
    model_fn(data),
    warning = function(w) {
      cat("Warning during fit:", conditionMessage(w), "\n")
      invokeRestart("muffleWarning")
    },
    error = function(e) {
      cat("Error during fit:", conditionMessage(e), "\n")
    }
  )
}
For pipelines this distinction is not academic. tar_make() uses calling handlers internally so that a failure in one target is logged and recorded, and the pipeline carries on with the targets that do not depend on the one that failed. Wholesale unwinding, the tryCatch behaviour, would throw away work that had nothing to do with the failure. Choosing the right handler is choosing whether a single failure is local or fatal.






NoteAnalogy: a fire alarm with two settings



tryCatch is a fire alarm that evacuates the whole building: everyone drops what they are doing and leaves by the nearest exit (the stack unwinds). withCallingHandlers is an alarm that merely sends a note to the front desk: the note is logged, perhaps an action is taken, and everyone keeps working. Pipelines usually want the second for individual task failures and the first only for genuinely unrecoverable problems.

7.3 R6: encapsulated, mutable, and built from environments
R6 is fundamentally different from S3 and S4, and it is where the whole book pays off, because an R6 object is an environment. Its methods are functions stored inside that environment, conventionally reached through self$ and private$. And because environments are passed by reference (Chapter 2), R6 objects do not copy when passed to functions. They behave like objects in Python or Java: hand the same object to two functions and both see each other’s changes.
library(R6)

Counter &lt;- R6Class("Counter",
  private = list(
    count = 0
  ),
  public = list(
    initialize = function(start = 0) {
      private$count &lt;- start
    },
    increment = function(by = 1) {
      private$count &lt;- private$count + by
      invisible(self)              # returning self enables chaining
    },
    value = function() {
      private$count
    }
  )
)

c &lt;- Counter$new(10)
c$increment()$increment(by = 5)
c$value()    # 16
Now compare this to make_counter from Chapter 3. The two have the same external behaviour: a counter with private, persistent state and methods to change and read it. Under R6, the count lives in the object’s private environment. Under the factory pattern, the count lived in the captured environment of the closures. Both are environments. The difference is purely the layer of convention R6 adds: explicit public and private sections, an automatic self, an inheritance system, and a constructor. R6 is closures wearing a uniform.






ImportantKey idea: encapsulated objects are environments



S3 and S4 attach behaviour to data through external generics; the data itself is inert. R6 puts the behaviour and the mutable state together inside one environment, and gets reference semantics for free because that is how environments already work. If you understood Chapters 2 and 3, you already understand R6; the rest is naming.

8.3 How a dependency is registered
Here is the part that feels like magic until you see it, and it is built entirely from Chapter 4’s promises. When the body of a reactive expression runs and reads input$x, two things happen at once. First, the current value of input$x is returned. Second, the reactive context that is currently running registers itself in input$x’s list of dependents.
From then on, whenever input$x changes, it walks its list of dependents and sends each one an invalidation signal. The dependents mark themselves invalid but do not recompute immediately. They wait until something actually asks for their value (a conductor) or until the next flush of the event loop (an observer).
library(shiny)

ui &lt;- fluidPage(
  numericInput("x", "x:", 1),
  numericInput("y", "y:", 1),
  textOutput("sum")
)

server &lt;- function(input, output) {

  total &lt;- reactive({
    cat("computing total\n")
    input$x + input$y         # reading these registers dependencies on both
  })

  output$sum &lt;- renderText({
    cat("rendering sum\n")
    paste("Sum:", total())    # reading total() registers a dependency on it
  })

  observe({
    cat("observed:", total(), "\n")   # also depends on total
  })
}
Draw the graph. input$x and input$y are sources. total is a conductor depending on both. output$sum and the observe() are endpoints, both depending on total. Change input$x and it invalidates total, which invalidates both endpoints. The body of total runs exactly once, and its cached value is reused by both consumers. That caching is precisely the closure-plus-table pattern from Chapter 3, and the reason total runs once rather than twice is the whole reason conductors exist.






ImportantKey idea: reading is subscribing



In a reactive context, reading a value is the same act as subscribing to it. You never write the subscription separately, which is exactly why the code reads like a plain formula. The dependency edge is created as a side effect of evaluating the expression, which is only possible because the expression is a lazily evaluated promise that runs inside a context that is watching what it touches.

10.3 Walking and rewriting code
Because a call is list-like, you can not only read its parts but change them.
e &lt;- quote(a + b)
e[[1]] &lt;- quote(`*`)   # replace the operator
e
#&gt; a * b
You can also walk an entire expression tree and compute something about it. Here is a small function that counts how many additions appear anywhere in an expression. It calls itself on each piece, which is safe here because expression trees are shallow (recall from Chapter 5 that bounded-depth recursion is fine in R; it is only deep iteration you must avoid).
count_adds &lt;- function(expr) {
  if (is.call(expr)) {
    here &lt;- if (identical(expr[[1]], quote(`+`))) 1 else 0
    here + sum(vapply(as.list(expr)[-1], count_adds, numeric(1)))
  } else {
    0   # a constant or a name contains no additions
  }
}

count_adds(quote((a + b) * (c + d + e)))
#&gt; [1] 3
Read what just happened: we wrote a program that takes another program as input and answers a question about it. That is metaprogramming in one breath. Tools like linters, code formatters, and coverage trackers are elaborate versions of count_adds.

11.2 Step 1: the simplest expressions
We begin lang_eval, our evaluator. Its two arguments are an expression and an environment, exactly the pair Chapter 9 told us we would need. The two easiest cases are constants and names.
lang_eval &lt;- function(expr, env) {
  # A constant evaluates to itself.
  if (is.numeric(expr) || is.character(expr) || is.logical(expr)) {
    return(expr)
  }
  # A name is a variable: look it up in the environment.
  if (is.symbol(expr)) {
    return(env_get(env, as.character(expr)))
  }
  stop("lang_eval: I do not yet understand: ", deparse(expr))
}
We can already evaluate the two simplest kinds of code. Note that we use quote() from Chapter 9 to hand our evaluator a piece of unevaluated code.
e &lt;- env_new(emptyenv())
env_set(e, "x", 10)

lang_eval(quote(42), e)    #&gt; 42      a constant is itself
lang_eval(quote(x), e)     #&gt; 10      a name is looked up
lang_eval(quote(y), e)     #&gt; Error: object 'y' not found
The constant returns itself. The name x is found in the environment. The name y is not, and the error comes from env_get walking the (empty) parent chain and finding nothing, precisely the lookup mechanism of Chapter 2.

11.3 Step 2: function calls
Now the interesting case: a call, such as 1 + 2. Recall from Chapter 9 that a call is a tree whose first element is the function and whose remaining elements are the argument expressions. To evaluate a call, we evaluate the function, evaluate each argument, and apply one to the others. For now our “functions” will be ordinary R primitives like +, which we can apply with do.call.
lang_eval &lt;- function(expr, env) {
  if (is.numeric(expr) || is.character(expr) || is.logical(expr)) {
    return(expr)
  }
  if (is.symbol(expr)) {
    return(env_get(env, as.character(expr)))
  }
  if (is.call(expr)) {
    fn   &lt;- lang_eval(expr[[1]], env)              # evaluate the function
    args &lt;- lapply(as.list(expr)[-1], lang_eval, env = env)  # evaluate args
    return(do.call(fn, args))                      # apply
  }
  stop("lang_eval: I do not understand: ", deparse(expr))
}
To make this run we need an environment in which the names +, *, and so on refer to the real arithmetic functions. This is our language’s global environment.
global_env &lt;- env_new(emptyenv())
env_set(global_env, "+", `+`)
env_set(global_env, "*", `*`)
env_set(global_env, "-", `-`)
env_set(global_env, "&lt;", `&lt;`)

lang_eval(quote(1 + 2), global_env)          #&gt; 3
lang_eval(quote(2 * (3 + 4)), global_env)    #&gt; 14
Trace the second one. The outer call is *. We evaluate its function: the name * is looked up in global_env and returns R’s multiplication function. We evaluate its two arguments: 2 is a constant, and 3 + 4 is itself a call, so lang_eval recurses, evaluates +, 3, and 4, and applies, giving 7. Then we apply * to 2 and 7, giving 14. Our evaluator is walking the tree exactly as Chapter 9 described, and the mutual recursion between evaluating and applying is already visible: a call’s arguments are evaluated by the very same function.

11.4 Step 3: a special form, if
Not everything can be handled by “evaluate all the arguments, then apply”. Consider if. If we evaluated both branches before choosing, an if guarding against an error would run the error anyway. So if must be handled specially: evaluate the condition, then evaluate only the chosen branch. Constructs that bend the normal evaluate-everything rule are called special forms, and every language has a handful.
We add a check for if before the general call case.
lang_eval &lt;- function(expr, env) {
  if (is.numeric(expr) || is.character(expr) || is.logical(expr)) {
    return(expr)
  }
  if (is.symbol(expr)) {
    return(env_get(env, as.character(expr)))
  }
  if (is.call(expr)) {
    op &lt;- expr[[1]]

    # Special form: if
    if (identical(op, quote(`if`))) {
      if (isTRUE(lang_eval(expr[[2]], env))) {
        return(lang_eval(expr[[3]], env))   # the "then" branch
      } else {
        return(lang_eval(expr[[4]], env))   # the "else" branch
      }
    }

    # General case: ordinary function application
    fn   &lt;- lang_eval(op, env)
    args &lt;- lapply(as.list(expr)[-1], lang_eval, env = env)
    return(do.call(fn, args))
  }
  stop("lang_eval: I do not understand: ", deparse(expr))
}
lang_eval(quote(if (1 &lt; 2) 10 else 20), global_env)   #&gt; 10
lang_eval(quote(if (5 &lt; 2) 10 else 20), global_env)   #&gt; 20

11.5 Step 4: functions of our own, with closures
So far our language can only use functions that already exist. The final step, and the one that makes this a real language, is letting our language define its own functions. This is where every idea from Part II comes together at once.
When our evaluator meets a function expression, it must build a closure. From Chapter 3 we know exactly what a closure is: the parameters, the body, and a pointer to the environment in which it was defined. We capture all three.
When our evaluator later applies one of these closures, it must, from Chapters 2 and 3: create a new environment whose parent is the closure’s definition environment (this is what makes scoping lexical), bind the arguments to the parameter names in that new environment, and evaluate the body there.
Here is the finished evaluator, with the function special form and a proper lang_apply that handles both R primitives and our own closures.
lang_eval &lt;- function(expr, env) {
  if (is.numeric(expr) || is.character(expr) || is.logical(expr)) {
    return(expr)
  }
  if (is.symbol(expr)) {
    return(env_get(env, as.character(expr)))
  }
  if (is.call(expr)) {
    op &lt;- expr[[1]]

    if (identical(op, quote(`if`))) {
      if (isTRUE(lang_eval(expr[[2]], env))) {
        return(lang_eval(expr[[3]], env))
      } else {
        return(lang_eval(expr[[4]], env))
      }
    }

    # Special form: function -&gt; build a closure that remembers its birthplace
    if (identical(op, quote(`function`))) {
      return(list(
        kind   = "closure",
        params = names(expr[[2]]),   # the parameter names
        body   = expr[[3]],          # the unevaluated body
        env    = env                 # the definition environment
      ))
    }

    # General case: evaluate the function and the arguments, then apply
    fn   &lt;- lang_eval(op, env)
    args &lt;- lapply(as.list(expr)[-1], lang_eval, env = env)
    return(lang_apply(fn, args))
  }
  stop("lang_eval: I do not understand: ", deparse(expr))
}

lang_apply &lt;- function(fn, args) {
  # A built-in R function (like + or *).
  if (is.function(fn)) {
    return(do.call(fn, args))
  }
  # One of our own closures.
  if (is.list(fn) && identical(fn$kind, "closure")) {
    call_env &lt;- env_new(parent = fn$env)            # new frame, parented at birthplace
    for (i in seq_along(fn$params)) {
      env_set(call_env, fn$params[[i]], args[[i]])  # bind arguments
    }
    return(lang_eval(fn$body, call_env))            # run the body there
  }
  stop("lang_apply: not something I can call")
}
Now the moment of truth. We will build, in our own language, the make_adder factory from Chapter 3, and check that it gets closures right.
add_maker &lt;- lang_eval(quote(function(n) function(x) x + n), global_env)

add5 &lt;- lang_apply(add_maker, list(5))
add9 &lt;- lang_apply(add_maker, list(9))

lang_apply(add5, list(10))   #&gt; 15
lang_apply(add9, list(10))   #&gt; 19
Stop and savour this. Our hand-written evaluator just produced two functions that share a body and behave differently, because each remembers a different n. We did not build special machinery for that. It fell out of one line in lang_apply, the line that parents the new environment at fn$env. Lexical scoping and closures are not features we added; they are consequences of where we pointed a parent pointer, exactly as the book has claimed since Chapter 2.






ImportantKey idea: the runtime is not magic, because you just built one



Every behaviour we have described across nine chapters, name lookup walking a parent chain, closures remembering their birthplace, the evaluate-then-apply rhythm of running a call, is now sitting in front of you as a few dozen lines of ordinary R. The interpreter that runs your real R code is vastly larger and faster, but it is the same shape. You are no longer guessing what the runtime does. You have written its essence.
